metadata.name: Convection Drawings #51
metadata.description:
This system is a composite of two generative layers: and invisible force field, and a swarm of particles that move around and leave an inky trail on the screen. There are only two forces at play: gravity towards the center, and repulsion between the particles, which becomes more or less strong depending on the underlying force field. In other words, it is like the particles “shrink” or “grow” depending on their position.
These simple conditions create emergent behavior with most particles moving in loops, analogous to convective cells in a fluid with heterogeneous densities. 
Press [m] to show the particles and see the system dynamics more clearly. You can also double click/tap anywhere on the screen to move the center of gravity and generate a different drawing from the same force field. 

This script will adapt nicely to any screen size and ratio.

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[Double click / tap] to relocate the center of gravity
[r] to recenter gravity and restart the drawing
[m] to toggle between path drawing and particle swarm views
[i] to reveal the hidden force field
[s] to download capture
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at 2x, 3x, … your viewport size (wait for the drawing to finish – might take longer at higher resolutions)

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Mar de lã #151
metadata.description:
"Once upon a time, in a land far, far away, there was a magical kingdom known for its beautiful landscapes and mystical creatures. The kingdom was ruled by a kind and fair queen, who loved nothing more than to spend her days exploring the vast and varied terrain of her realm.

One day, the queen was wandering through a particularly cold and snowy region of the kingdom when she came upon a strange sight. Instead of snow, the ground was covered with soft, fluffy balls of wool, as if the earth itself had been transformed into a giant ball of yarn.

The queen was fascinated by this curious phenomenon, and she decided to follow the trail of wool to see where it led. After walking for some time, she came upon a beautiful lake, the surface of which was frozen solid. But instead of ice, the lake was made entirely of woolen fibers, swirling and twirling in the gentle breeze.

The queen marveled at the sight, and she couldn't help but reach out and touch the soft, velvety surface of the woolen lake. As she did, she felt a warmth and comfort wash over her, as if the wool were alive and pulsing with energy.

Over the years, the queen visited the woolen lake often, always feeling a sense of peace and contentment when she was near it. And as the years went by, the people of the kingdom began to flock to the woolen lake, seeking the same sense of warmth and comfort that the queen had found.

The woolen lake became a beloved and sacred place in the kingdom, and it was known throughout the land as the "mar de lã" - the sea of wool. And so it remained, a magical and mystical place that brought joy and happiness to all who visited."
_AI GPT

metadata.name: Der Ast #103
metadata.description:
Der Ast is a work which grew from a love of triganometry. The tree grows and branches 
based on a fixed and finite set of rules and while this leads to some very self-similar 
structures, in some cases, it generally allows for some very detailed complexity and 
surprise overall.

In this system, a box is drawn and on top of it, a right-angled triangle. The triangle
has an α angle conforming to a set formula (for example, in one system the angle follows)
a sinewave along the bough). From this triangle we construct the next square/triangle
set upon the hypotenuse and, if the β is wide enough, a second branch sprouts from the 
adjacent side.

This work is intended to be printed, and so included are controls to allow you to download
a high-resolution version as well as to create any aspect you wish.

- Append &dpr=x to the URL where DPR is the pixel density you want. This defaults to 2
- Append &fs=true to the URL to scale the token to the size of your browser
- Append &width=x and &height=y to the URL to scale the token to a specific size

Double-click/tap to download.

metadata.name: Kaibō #138
metadata.description:
What would happen if we took the natural forms that surround us and dissected them into composable shapes? 

Taking the organic world of Yashinoki, Kiabō dissects organic forms into composable elements, then reforms them into precise geometric arrangements. These shapes give way to random, organic growth the closer we look at them. 


Controls in live mode:
- Press [s] to save a png

Made with code by AutoEclectus.

metadata.name: Nullteilung #49
metadata.description:
Nullteilung is another exercise in suprematism and composition. Born from a series of exercises in subdevision and tesselation, it seeks to connect with the user through the creation of a sense of order and balance in the composition.

The term "Nullteilung" a German word that can be translated to "zero division" which is suggesative of the order and disorder paramount in the piece, working toward a goal of emotional and programmatic purity.
